-----
[[div_ class="newspaper-body"]]
[[include component:image-block
    name=https://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/fragment%3Ascp-6500-4/nature-animal-bear-wildlife-zoo-backyard-mammal-garden-fauna-panda-endangered-vertebrate-china-bamboo-giant-panda-891136.jpg |
    caption=Toph-Lin, a Panda that escaped from Wilson's Wildlife Services during the event.
]]

[[size 250%]]O[[/size]]n Monday, chaos reigned in Boring as dozens of animals from Wilson's Wildlife Services broke through the front gates and flooded the streets.

The animals were apparently released by Faeowynn Wilson, owner of Wilson's Wildlife Services, an animal rescue facility famous throughout Clackamas County for its variety of exotic and bizarre wildlife, which the organization terms 'critters'. The facility was in danger of shutting down following a period of what an official statement from Ms. Wilson called 'global environmental decline that... is detrimental to the ecosystems that support our critters'.

However, Wilson's Wildlife Services experienced a massive resurgence in business in the past month, following what was officially reported as a meteor strike in the middle of the facility. The object, which resembled an indigo shard of glass, had been on display in Wilson's Wildlife Service's main building as part of a fundraising effort. This item apparently played a key, but unknown, role in this event.

In the early hours of Monday morning, a pair of unknown individuals, a white woman with red hair in her late thirties, and an African-American male in their mid-to-late forties, arrived at the front gate of the Wilson's Wildlife complex with several members of the Clackamas County Sheriff's Department in tow. Ms. Wilson was seen letting them into the facility. Up to 8:00 AM, several witnesses reported bursts of indigo light originating from within the WWS facility; then, at 8:07, when children were preparing to go to school, several animals broke loose.

Witnesses report that Ms. Wilson was seen riding astride an animal described as a 'unicorn with... claws instead of hooves', holding the indigo meteorite. It was speculated that she was using the meteorite to control this animal and several others. These reports are unsubstantiated, but currently under investigation by the //Chronicle//.

Notable incidents of damage include the razing of Boring's pre-school facilities by a 'giant wombat', a small forest fire set by 'deers[sic] with flaming antlers', and several individuals reporting strange dreams following the sighting of a tapir within the town's unincorporated area.

Furthermore, the two individuals seen entering the Wilson's Wildlife complex in the early hours of the morning appeared to have been attempting to engage in a dialog with Ms. Wilson; this reporter attempted to approach one of them but was declined any comment, as they were engaged in combat with what appeared to be a sheep that was emitting large amounts of electricity.

Remarkably, there were no fatalities and only one injury; a woman, whose name has not been released to the Boring Chronicle, was apparently gored by the 'unicorn' that Ms. Wilson was riding, but is reportedly in stable condition at a hospital in Portland.

Ms. Wilson is currently in police custody, having surrendered herself after the goring incident; an oral statement was obtained:

"I'm not sure how much I can tell you. But what's been happening for years now is... things have been dying. An ecological crisis, like none of you are aware of. The critters are just one part of it, and when I saw the gemstone coming from the sky, saw that it was revitalizing the critters in their pens I couldn't help myself. I held onto it, and when my Supervisors came to collect it, I got mad. I wanted the animals to protect themselves, and... I swear to god, they let themselves out of their own [expletive] cages when I grabbed the gem. Bauble. //Codex//, she called it, if you can believe that. I told them to protect themselves, and... that's what they did."

The whereabouts of several of the animals are currently unknown. An organization called Stop Cruelty towards Pets has been handed temporary ownership of Wilson's Wildlife Services, and Montgomery Reynolds, a spokesperson for the organization, assured the Chronicle that they will "continue to provide services equivalent to or greater in quality" than those provided by Wilson's Wildlife Services.
